On Sat, 2004-06-19 at 03:06, Justin Knowlden wrote:
&gt; Under (at least) J2SDK 1.4, you can pass an instance of PrintStream to
&gt; System.setOut(), .setErr(), and .setIn(). For instance, you can do the
&gt; following to capture stdout and stderr:
&gt;  
&gt; [...]
&gt; public void testMyTest() throws Exception {
&gt;   ByteArrayOutputStream stdout = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
&gt;   ByteArrayOutputStream stderr = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
&gt;   System.setOut(stdout);
&gt;   System.setErr(stderr);
&gt;   [...]
&gt; }
&gt; [...]
&gt;
&gt; Replace ByteArrayOutputStream with FileOutputStream to print to a file.
&gt; I haven&#39;t checked, but this probably works with JDK 1.3 as well.

It works with at least Java 1.2 and higher.  I&#39;ve done this often; one
thing that I have found to be worthwhile, though, is to put things back
the way I found them after the test.  Hence:

public void setUp() {
    OutputStream origOut = System.out;
    System.setOut(new ByteArrayOutputStream();
}

public void tearDown() {
    System.setOut(origOut);
}

that way, the test hopefully won&#39;t have any impact on anything that
happens after it completes.

